<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1615,1640]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Description.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[361,457,1615,1640]" captionStart="FIGURE 116" captionStartId="185.[151,250,1684,1706]" captionTargetBox="[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@185.[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetPageId="185" captionText="FIGURE 116. Hymeniacidon heliophila (Wilson, 1911), a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9923 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of surface skeleton, c – c 1, SEM images of the spicules, c, various shapes of styles, c 1, details of c." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273066/files/figure.png" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
a) Irregular stringy lobes and thin branches, presumably detached from a buried main body, which was not collected. Also thin encrustations on dead shells and carbonate rubble.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" box="[199,1298,1687,1712]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1687,1712]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Skeleton.</emphasis>
Loosely confused arrangement in the choanosome, tangential at the surface (
<figureCitation box="[1174,1270,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 116" captionStartId="185.[151,250,1684,1706]" captionTargetBox="[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@185.[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetPageId="185" captionText="FIGURE 116. Hymeniacidon heliophila (Wilson, 1911), a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9923 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of surface skeleton, c – c 1, SEM images of the spicules, c, various shapes of styles, c 1, details of c." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273066/files/figure.png" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" box="[199,609,1724,1749]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1724,1749]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Spicules.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[319,421,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURE 116" captionStartId="185.[151,250,1684,1706]" captionTargetBox="[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@185.[147,1432,513,1662]" captionTargetPageId="185" captionText="FIGURE 116. Hymeniacidon heliophila (Wilson, 1911), a, habitus of RMNH Por. 9923 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, light microscopic image of surface skeleton, c – c 1, SEM images of the spicules, c, various shapes of styles, c 1, details of c." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273066/files/figure.png" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Figs 116</figureCitation>
c,c1) Styles only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" box="[199,1163,1759,1784]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
Styles, straight or slightly curved, often with faint tyle, 320– 
<emphasis box="[875,915,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">411</emphasis>
–479 
<date box="[977,1010,1760,1784]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">x 3</date>
– 
<emphasis box="[1027,1062,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">7.6</emphasis>
–9.5 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,498,1796,1821]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
Originally described from 
<collectingRegion box="[800,971,1796,1821]" country="United States of America" name="North Carolina" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
North 
<collectingRegion box="[872,971,1796,1821]" country="Puerto Rico" name="Carolina" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Carolina</collectingRegion>
</collectingRegion>
, the species has been reported throughout the Caribbean region and also from 
<collectingCountry box="[590,658,1831,1856]" name="Brazil" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Muricy 
<emphasis box="[777,839,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">et al.</emphasis>
2011). Predominantly known from shallow-water, intertidal and mangrove habitats. The present records from sandy bottoms at 
<quantity box="[1009,1122,1868,1893]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.45" metricValueMax="13.0" metricValueMin="5.9" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" unit="m" value="94.5" valueMax="130.0" valueMin="59.0">59–130 m</quantity>
depth are by far the deepest occurrence known for the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="185" lastPageNumber="186" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="184.[151,1436,1471,2037]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1940,1965]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Remarks.</emphasis>
In view of the deep occurrence there is some doubt about the identification. However, similarity with the original description and subsequent morphological information does not warrant erecting a new species for the 
<collectingCountry box="[232,319,2012,2036]" name="Guyana" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Guyana</collectingCountry>
Shelf material.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="185.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1424726557" collectionCode="ICZN" collectorName="Authorship &amp; Parker &amp; De Laubenfels &amp; However &amp; H. V. Wilson &amp; Apart" location="Central West" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Central West" typeStatus="holotype">
<collectorName box="[199,325,151,176]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Authorship</collectorName>
of this common 
<collectingRegion box="[546,699,151,176]" isEnumeration="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Central West</collectingRegion>
Atlantic species has been assigned to 
<bibRefCitation author="Parker" box="[1183,1345,151,176]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" refString="Parker, G. H. (1910) The reactions of sponges, with a consideration of the origin of the nervous system. Journal of Experimental Zoology, 8, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1910">
<collectorName box="[1183,1256,151,176]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Parker</collectorName>
(1910)
</bibRefCitation>
by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="185" pageNumber="186" refString="De Laubenfels, M. W. (1936) A discussion of the sponge fauna of the Dry Tortugas, in particular, and the West Indies in general, with material for a revision of the families and orders of the Porifera. Carnegie Institution of Washington Publication, 467 (Tortugas Laboratory Paper, 30, 1 - 225." type="journal article">
<collectorName pageId="185" pageNumber="186">De Laubenfels</collectorName>
(1936)
</bibRefCitation>
(p.138). 
<collectorName box="[458,562,189,212]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">However</collectorName>
, 
<collectorName box="[573,646,188,213]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Parker</collectorName>
himself (1910) (p. 2) made it abundantly clear that 
<collectorName box="[1221,1358,188,213]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">H.V. Wilson</collectorName>
was in the process of describing this species and he only ‘borrowed’ the name for his physiological study. 
<collectorName box="[1288,1352,224,248]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Apart</collectorName>
from a figure of the species, there is no taxonomic description, nor a 
<typeStatus box="[909,957,261,285]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">type</typeStatus>
specimen assignment in Parker’s paper. Effectively, Parker’s use of the name is a 
<emphasis box="[661,824,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">nomen nudum</emphasis>
in the sense of the 
<collectionCode box="[1075,1144,296,320]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">ICZN</collectionCode>
</materialsCitation>
. Authorship and year of publication should go to 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson" box="[433,597,332,357]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" refString="Wilson, H. V. (1911) Development of sponges from dissociated tissue cells. Bulletin of the Bureau of Fisheries, 30, 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="1911">Wilson (1911)</bibRefCitation>
, who gave a taxonomic description including information on the spicules. ICZN Art. 50.1 clearly stipulates the case that Parker’s (1910) referral to Wilson as the author of a forthcoming publication, in which the species is to be properly described, is a valid nomenclatorial procedure. In conclusion 
<taxonomicName authority="Wilson, 1911" authorityName="Wilson" authorityYear="1911" box="[151,609,439,464]" class="Demospongiae" family="Halichondriidae" genus="Hymeniacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="heliophila">
<emphasis box="[151,435,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Hymeniacidon heliophila</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson" box="[449,601,439,464]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" refString="Wilson, H. V. (1911) Development of sponges from dissociated tissue cells. Bulletin of the Bureau of Fisheries, 30, 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="1911">Wilson, 1911</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is the proper author-year combination for this species.
</paragraph>
